# A [[cant]] used in the London fishmarkets, in the British theatre, and by the homosexual community in Britain, attested since at least the 19th century and popularised in the 1950s and 1960s by the camp characters Julian and Sandy in the popular [[w:BBC|BBC]] radio show ''{{w|Round the Horne}}''.
# A [[cant]] used by travelling showmen in Britain.

====Usage notes====
Some authors, like Paul Baker, contrast {{m|en|Polari}} and {{m|en|Parlyaree}}, using the former for the gay cant, and the latter for the older cant of actors and circus and fairground showmen.<ref>Paul Baker, ''Polari&nbsp;– The Lost Language of Gay Men'', Routledge 2003, passim</ref>

